AGI - The dynamics of the death of an elderly passenger on the flight<a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-21/singapore-airlines-turbolenza-morto-feriti-26472795/"> Singapore Airlines </a> departed from London and forced today to an emergency landing in Bangkok after crossing a violent turbulence. What is certain is that this is a very rare but not unprecedented event. Since 1979, or since modern satellite systems allow to detect them, turbulence has caused the death of three people on board commercial flights, the last of which in 2009, reports the Federal Aviation Administration > (Faa) of the United States.
&nbsp;
The few seconds when an air vacuum causes the rapid loss of plane share can be remembered as one of the most terrifying of one's life even by a person who is not afraid to fly and, in fact, would have been a heart attack to break the lost passenger on the London-Singapore route. If you are sitting in your seat with the seat belt and the closed table the risk of getting hurt is very low. If you are standing you can get banged violently against the ceiling or hats or be hit by luggage and other items in the cabin. That is why 80% of the 146 people wounded in a "serious" way on line flights from 2009 to 2022 are members of the crew, who when serving meals are likely to be overwhelmed by a heavy cart carrying hot drinks.&nbsp;
<h2>But what are turbulence?</h2>
The turbulence is an irregular air movement that causes sudden changes in altitude or angle of attack of the plane. The causes can be multiple: atmospheric pressure, air around the mountains, storms or jet currents, fast airflows in the upper levels of the atmosphere. The turbulence is classified in three categories: the "light", which at the height of the cruise concern 3% of the atmosphere; the "moderates", which concern 1%, and the "severe", whose incidence is limited to a few decimals. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"There is light turbulence, which puts a little hard to test the safety belt, but the catering service can continue and you can probably walk through the cabin, perhaps with some difficulties", explained Professor Paul Williams, professor of meteorology at the University of Reading, "then there is a moderate turbulence, a certain tension for the seat belts, all that is not fixed moves and walking is difficult; flight attendants are usually asked to take a seat." Finally, the worst, severe turbulence. "It's stronger than gravity, so it can nail you to the seat and if you don't wear the seat belt you'll get kicked inside the cabin," explains the academy, "this is the kind of turbulence that causes serious injuries, such as fractures."
&nbsp;
One of the most dangerous types of turbulence is that known as turbulence in free air, which does not give any visible warning and often occurs when riders did not turn on the signal of the attached safety belt. "It is completely invisible to the naked eye, radar, satellites," explains the meteorologist, "we only know when a plane crosses it." And it is a phenomenon that, according to many experts, is destined to increase due to climate change, that&nbsp; is causing greater instability in jet currents and accelerating the speed of the wind.
&nbsp;
Nature had established a 17% increase in jet currents compared to 1979. And, according to Professor Williams, in 2050 drivers will have to expect to deal with double the turbulence in free air recorded at the moment. But, reassuring, a turbulence is not able to crash a line plane. Less reassuring data on private ultralight jets, which when they cross an intense turbulence risk crashing on the ground. According to the Faa, on this type of aircraft the turbulence have collected 38 victims from 2009 to 2022.&nbsp;
